An Analysis on Inflation in Turkey¶

Alkım Can Çelik¶
2018402222¶

Introduction¶

The aim of this project is to measure and analyze the inflation between 2017-2020. The data are obtained from the Central Bank of the Republic of Turkey.

The following datasets which are essential in our analysis are used:

  • USD-TRY Exchange Rate
  • Unemployment Rate
  • Interest Rates

The main goal is to get insights about the policies determined by the government and the real reasons of the inflation.

You can find the codes here.

CPI has increased in each month. It is obvious that the increase rate increases for two months, then decreases for two months again in general. There are violations absolutely but the similarities between these periods should be taken into consideration.

It is interesting that the interest rate does not seem in strong relation with the CPI according to this graph. However, a sudden increase after July 2018 was observed, which was also seen for CPI at the same time. In addition, like the increase, a sudden decrease was observed, like in CPI. These are similarities between these graphs. However, most significant increases and decreases are not matched with the CPI graph.

There was an increasing trend between January 2017 and 2019 for 2 years. Then, it had decreased generally until April 2020. Then, a short increasing period exists. In general, the trendline has a very slight downward curve.

The sudden upward shift may an indication of the wrong economic decisions made by the government. Firstly, in August 2018, the Central Bank of Turkish Republic announced the highest inflation for 15 years. Then, due to this inflation rate, they decided to reorganize some regulations in the monetary system, which results in higher interest rate. Also, it is related to the exchange rate, but it will be discussed later.

USD-TRY exchange rates will be chosen because it is the hottest topic for the society compared to the other currencies.

The time frame will be 4 years, between 01/01/2017 and 31/12/2020.

In [19]:
USD_TRY = evds.get_data(["TP.DK.USD.A.YTL"], startdate="01-01-2017", enddate="31-12-2020")
USD_TRY.head(10)
Out[19]:
Tarih TP_DK_USD_A_YTL

1 02-01-2017 3.5192
2 03-01-2017 3.5338
3 04-01-2017 3.5737

5 06-01-2017 3.5934
6 07-01-2017 NaN
7 08-01-2017 NaN
8 09-01-2017 3.6134
9 10-01-2017 3.7020

The frequency of the observations is daily.

As you can see, there are missing data. The reason is that the market is closed on weekends. Therefore, the days at the weekends have no exchange rate.

Linear interpolation will be used to fill the data. It is a very popular method for missing data, and also it is logical because the increase in exchange rate at the weekends likely happens in a gradual way. This assumption can be hold in this assignment.

For linear interpolation, there should be beginning and ending points. Since 01/01/2017 is Sunday, there is no beginning point for interpolation. Therefore, the exchange rate on the next Monday, will be used.

In [20]:
USD_TRY = USD_TRY.interpolate(method = "linear")
USD_TRY.iloc[0,1] = USD_TRY.iloc[1,1] 
USD_TRY.head(10)

The dashed red line indicates the trend. As you can see, there is an upward trend for 4 years in USD-TRY exchange rate. There are some decreases in some days, but in general, the exchange rate has increased. It was more than doubled after 4 years. From the beginning of 2017 to March and April 2018, the rate was staying almost same. However, after April 2018, the rate was almost doubled until September 2018. Then, it was decreased, but not returned to the previous level. It can be seen that, the exchange rate generally increases in the second half of the years.

In my opinion, there is no seasonal similarity as it can be seen from the graph. Since it is exchange rate, there should not be a pattern. This is against the rules of economics. The exchange rate should be unpredictable.

The reason that we have an upward trend like this may be that the current government in Turkey has had bad policies in the economy. The production rate has decreased for 10 years. Our export rate has also decreased, import rate has increased. The political instability has also affected the foreign investors' trust, which results in diminishing investments in Turkey. The justice in Turkey has not been carried out properly for 20 years. These are main reasons for the increase in exchange rate.

The main reason for sudden decreases is the decreased the increase rate, as mentioned above. When the plots are compared, it can be clearly seen that there is a negative relation between them.

In this graph, the red dashed line indicates that there is an upward trend in unemployment rate. There are several reasons for that, such as increase in young employee population, At first, there was a sudden decrease in the rate about 4% in 4 months. When we analyze the plot, we can realize that the rate starts to decrease after the January. New Year decisions may be effective for this pattern. In addition, the unemployment rate seems to increase in summers. Seasonal fluctuations are observed in this graph.

The unemployment rate was steady between May 2017 and April 2018. Then, it increased from 9% to 15% between May 2018 and January 2019. This may come from the decisions made by the Central Bank after July 2018, as discussed above. Inflation and unemployment rate are negatively correlated in theory. The sudden decrease in CPI may have resulted in increase in the unemployment rate. After this date, the rate have not fallen under 12%, as opposed to earlier dates. Therefore, the trendline is upward.

The unemployment rate data is monthly data, but the timeframe of search volume is weekly. It needs to be transformed into monthly.

In [40]:
iskur["Week"] = pd.to_datetime(iskur["Week"], yearfirst = True)
iskur = iskur.sort_values("Week")
iskur["Month"] = iskur["Week"].dt.month
iskur["Year"] = iskur["Week"].dt.year
iskur_grouped = iskur.groupby(["Month", "Year"], as_index = False)["işkur: (Turkey)"].sum()
iskur_grouped["Date"] = iskur_grouped["Year"].astype(str) + "-" + iskur_grouped["Month"].astype(str)
iskur_grouped["Date"] = pd.to_datetime(iskur_grouped["Date"])
iskur_grouped = iskur_grouped.sort_values("Date")

After this date, both have not returned their previous values. One interesting thing is that people searched this keyword in March 2020 a lot, but the unemployment rate was not surprising. The reason is that İŞKUR started to hire people in this month.

Key Takeaways¶

  • CPI does not seem good metric about how Turkey's economy is getting worse. The reason may be the lack of integrity of data due to political issues.
  • Interest rate and the USD-TRY exchange rate seem to have an autocorrelative relationship, as expected.
  • Unemployment rate should have decreased in theory due to increasing inflation, but it has an upward trend.
  • September 2018 is a turning point for Turkey's economy. After this date, all unfavorable rates have increased.
  • The search volume of the related keywords is very important to capture the sudden increases in the measure of interests.
